[5] Venezuela
Date: Sat 8 Feb 2020
Source: The Express [abridged, edited]
https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1084550/Venezuela-crisis-measles-outbreak-South-America-vaccination


Venezuela is in the throes of a political uprising, as opposition leader Juan Guaido wrests power from incumbent president Nicolas Maduro. An outbreak of measles in the country has only added to the current chaos.

Measles outbreaks have passed over the world from 2018-2019, infecting 10s of thousands of people and killing thousands more. The resurgence of the once near-eradicated disease has been blamed on "vaccine hesitancy" as people are refusing to vaccinate against measles. In Venezuela, vaccine coverage is at an all-time low, and political disturbance has only exacerbated the problem. Researchers have been following the outbreak and recommended exactly what should be done by Venezuelan and international authorities.

Researchers from the University of Groningen analysed funding and vaccine coverage in Venezuela and found just above half of the country was vaccinated.

They said: "The Venezuelan national funding level for the 2nd dose of the measles vaccine (1st dose at 14 months and the 2nd at 9 years old) is estimated at 52% on the basis of data from the Venezuelan Ministry of Public Health.

"The report contains data for a period of 16 months (June 2017-October 2018), in which a total of 7524 suspected cases of measles have been reported in Venezuela."

The team of researchers found some 66% of the country is living in extreme poverty as a result of hyperinflation and declining oil sales under Nicolas Maduro. With the economic struggles has also come social upheaval, with escalating violence and crumbling healthcare forcing people out of the country.

Some 280 000 children are at risk of dying under these conditions according to the researchers, and Venezuela is unlikely to see an end any time soon.

As a result, the researchers have warned against a developing measles epidemic. They have also touched on the measles cases from Venezuela eventually spilling over into neighbouring South American countries and local native populations.

The researchers said: "The measles outbreak also affects indigenous people in the Amazon and the Orinoco river delta. In addition, as a result of the recent refugee influx, measles infections are also detected in Brazil, Colombia, and Ecuador."

The team of researchers have outlined how Venezuelan health officials could best deal with measles.

How should Venezuela battle the measles outbreak?

Adriana Tami, a Venezuelan researcher from the University of Groningen's Department of Medical Microbiology, outlined how Venezuela could tackle the outbreak.

She said: "World Health Authorities should urge the Venezuelan government to allow humanitarian aid to address the extreme shortages of food and medicines immediately."

"In addition," she added, "the emergency aid (both nutrition and vaccinations) should be given not only in Venezuela but also together with Colombian and Brazilian authorities, for example, to limit the consequences of mass migration."

